(55, 1, '2010-07-11 11:01:17', '2010-07-11 10:01:17', 'I had to fix a bug today where the client reported that the dates on a page were all in French. She had set her browser language to French (apparently without realising).\n\nLocalisation is an area that I am ashamedly unfamiliar with, so I did some digging.\n\nI set my browser language to French (fr) and sure enough the dates appeared in French. I looked at Thread.CurrentThread.CurrentCulture.EnglishName and that was "French", so the culture was being picked up from the browser.\n\nAs this site is not set up for localisation, I opted to override the current culture in the web.config:\n<pre class="brush:csharp">&lt;configuration&gt;\n    &lt;system.web&gt;\n        &lt;globalization culture="en-GB" uiCulture="en-GB" /&gt;\n    &lt;/system.web&gt;\n&lt;/configuration&gt;</pre>\n<blockquote>The culture attribute enables you to define the culture to use for processing incoming requests, whereas the uiCulture attribute enables you define the default culture needed to process any resource files in the application.</blockquote>\nThat fixed my bug and the code stayed the same but gave me an English date for the GB culture.\n<pre class="brush:csharp">CurrentItem.Published.ToLongDateString()</pre>', 'DateTime, ToString(), and CurrentCulture', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '35-autosave', '', '', '2010-07-11 11:01:17', '2010-07-11 10:01:17', '', 35, 'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/15/35-autosave/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
