(75, 1, '2010-04-28 10:18:35', '2010-04-28 09:18:35', '<pre class="brush:csharp">var minutesRegex = /\\d+(?=m)/;\r\nvar minutesMatch = minutesRegex.exec(timeString)\r\n\r\nif (minutesMatch) {\r\n	var minutes = minutesMatch[0];\r\n}</pre>\r\n<h3>The regular expression</h3>\r\n\\d matches any digit\r\n\r\n+ matches one or more\r\n\r\n(?=m) is a zero-width positive lookahead, it matches "m" but doesn''t include it in the result of the match eg. t(?=s) matches the secondÂ t inÂ streets (<a href="http://www.regular-expressions.info/refadv.html">http://www.regular-expressions.info/refadv.html</a>). It will match "10" in the string "2h 10m 30s"\r\n<h3>References</h3>\r\n<a href="http://www.regular-expressions.info/javascript.html">http://www.regular-expressions.info/javascript.html</a>', 'Javascript Regex \\d+(?=m)', 'An example and explaination of a zero-width positive lookahead regex in JavaScript.', 'publish', 'open', 'open', '', 'javascript-regex', '', '', '2010-05-15 23:15:18', '2010-05-15 22:15:18', '', 0, 'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/?p=75', 0, 'post', '', 0),
