(101, 1, '2010-04-22 12:28:09', '2010-04-22 11:28:09', 'The biggest problem I have come across trying to create a new EPiServer project using the deployment tool from EPiServer is that it creates an IIS 7 website on your machine and references files and assemblies (in the Program Files folder) on your machine. This is fine if you are the only person in the team and work on the same machine all the time, and are happy to install EPiServer on your web server. I''m going to go through the steps required to create a new EPiServer project that can be run from the Visual Studio development web server and checked into source control, and most importantly will work when aÂ collegeÂ checks out a version.\r\n<h3><span style="font-weight: normal;">Just an EPiServer site</span></h3>\r\nOpen Visual Studio 2008 and create a new project using the EPiServer Project template. The visual studio template comes bundled with the main EPiServer 6 download.\r\n\r\nNext, create a new database. Open the EPiServer Deployment Center, and select Install SQL Server Database. Update the website connection string with the new database details.\r\n\r\nNext, go to the website properties page, and on the Web tab, remove the virtual path. And in the EPiServer.config file change the siteUrl in the siteSettings element.\r\n\r\nNow you should be able to launch the website and navigate to <strong>http://localhost:6666/EPiServer</strong> and login using your Windows credentials.\r\n<h3><span style="font-weight: normal;">Move the Program Files</span></h3>\r\nThe EPiServer.config file contains a virtualPath section, with provider entries that have paths to files on your local drive. This will be a problem when you try to check in the website to source control, or publish the webiste.\r\n\r\nTo fix this we need to copy the files to the website folder and specify a new provider type.\r\n\r\nCopy the whole EPiServer folder from C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer to your website directory. I want to keep the folder structure in tact, the less we have to tinker with it the better I think (although I have deleted the help folders - they''re huge!). <strong>Be sure to rename it otherwise the path provider won''t kick in.</strong>\r\n\r\nNext update the EPiServer.config provider entries, for example:\r\n\r\n&lt;add name="UIFiles" virtualPath="~/EPiServer/CMS/" physicalPath="C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS" type="EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider,EPiServer" /&gt;\r\n\r\nbecomes\r\n\r\n&lt;add name="UIFiles" virtualPath="~/EPiServer/CMS/" physicalPath="~\\EPiServerFiles\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS" type="Cubeworks.EPiServer6Site.RelativePathProvider,Cubeworks.EPiServer6Site" /&gt;\r\n\r\nNotice I have changed the type of provider to RelativePathProvider. (You may need to make a small change to the web.config file to make the website pickup the new configuration.)\r\n\r\n<strong>RelativePathProvider</strong>\r\n<pre class="brush:csharp">public class RelativePathProvider : EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider\r\n{\r\n	public RelativePathProvider(string providerName, NameValueCollection configParameters)\r\n		: base(providerName, FixConfig(configParameters))\r\n	{\r\n	}\r\n	private static NameValueCollection FixConfig(NameValueCollection configParameters)\r\n	{\r\n		var virtualPath = configParameters["physicalPath"] ?? String.Empty;\r\n		if(virtualPath.StartsWith("~"))\r\n			configParameters["physicalPath"] = HostingEnvironment.MapPath(virtualPath);\r\n		return configParameters;\r\n	}\r\n}</pre>\r\nFor the PageFiles, Globals, and Documents folders, I''ve simply moved them into a folder above the root of the website and modified the physical paths. This is not an ideal solution as the path will change on different machines, but I''m going to live with it for now.\r\n<h2>Install the Public Templates</h2>\r\nI used the EPiServer deployment centre to do this. It needs your website to be set up in IIS before it can access it. Create a new IIS website pointing to your EPiServer site. Set the physical path to your site directory and set a host name (that you can put in your hosts file to access the site).\r\n\r\nStart the EPiServer DeploymentÂ CentreÂ and select "Install Public Templates". Select your website from the list and click install.\r\n\r\nThis should add a Templates directory to your website and add some pages to the database too.\r\n<h2 style="font-size: 1.5em;">Move assemblies</h2>\r\nAlso, move the referenced assemblies in the web project to a folder with your solution files so they can be checked in. Make sure you re-add the references to the projetc from the new location and set "Copy Local" to true.', 'Creating a new EPiServer 6 Solution', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '50-revision-16', '', '', '2010-04-22 12:28:09', '2010-04-22 11:28:09', '', 50, 'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/22/50-revision-16/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(102, 1, '2010-05-10 16:15:07', '2010-05-10 15:15:07', '<div id="_mcePaste">\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">To create a new EPiServer 6 project you have 2 options. Either use the Deployment Centre (installed with EPiServer) or use the EPiServer Visual Studio template.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">The biggest problem with using the deployment tool is that it creates an IIS 7 website on your machine and references files and assemblies (in the Program Files folder) on your machine. This is fine if you are the only person in the team and work on the same machine all the time, and are happy to install EPiServer on your web server. It also creates the website in IIS 7 which is not ideal if you are running IIS6 on the web server.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">I''m going to go through the steps required to create a new EPiServer project that can be run from the Visual Studio development web server and checked into source control, and most importantly will work when a colleage checks out a version.</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h3><span style="font-weight: normal;">Just an EPiServer site</span></h3>\r\nOpen Visual Studio 2008 and create a new project using the EPiServer Project template. The visual studio template comes bundled with the main EPiServer 6 download.\r\n\r\nNext, create a new database. Open the EPiServer Deployment Center, and select Install SQL Server Database. Update the website connection string with the new database details.\r\n\r\nNext, go to the website properties page, and on the Web tab, remove the virtual path. And in the EPiServer.config file change the siteUrl in the siteSettings element.\r\n\r\nNow you should be able to launch the website and navigate to <strong>http://localhost:6666/EPiServer</strong> and login using your Windows credentials.\r\n<h3><span style="font-weight: normal;">Move the Program Files</span></h3>\r\nThe EPiServer.config file contains a virtualPath section, with provider entries that have paths to files on your local drive. This will be a problem when you try to check in the website to source control, or publish the webiste.\r\n\r\nTo fix this we need to copy the files to the website folder and specify a new provider type.\r\n\r\nCopy the whole EPiServer folder from C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer to your website directory. I want to keep the folder structure in tact, the less we have to tinker with it the better I think (although I have deleted the help folders - they''re huge!). <strong>Be sure to rename it otherwise the path provider won''t kick in.</strong>\r\n\r\nNext update the EPiServer.config provider entries, for example:\r\n\r\n&lt;add name="UIFiles" virtualPath="~/EPiServer/CMS/" physicalPath="C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS" type="EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider,EPiServer" /&gt;\r\n\r\nbecomes\r\n\r\n&lt;add name="UIFiles" virtualPath="~/EPiServer/CMS/" physicalPath="~\\EPiServerFiles\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS" type="Cubeworks.EPiServer6Site.RelativePathProvider,Cubeworks.EPiServer6Site" /&gt;\r\n\r\nNotice I have changed the type of provider to RelativePathProvider. (You may need to make a small change to the web.config file to make the website pickup the new configuration.)\r\n\r\n<strong>RelativePathProvider</strong>\r\n<pre class="brush:csharp">public class RelativePathProvider : EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider\r\n{\r\n	public RelativePathProvider(string providerName, NameValueCollection configParameters)\r\n		: base(providerName, FixConfig(configParameters))\r\n	{\r\n	}\r\n	private static NameValueCollection FixConfig(NameValueCollection configParameters)\r\n	{\r\n		var virtualPath = configParameters["physicalPath"] ?? String.Empty;\r\n		if(virtualPath.StartsWith("~"))\r\n			configParameters["physicalPath"] = HostingEnvironment.MapPath(virtualPath);\r\n		return configParameters;\r\n	}\r\n}</pre>\r\nFor the PageFiles, Globals, and Documents folders, I''ve simply moved them into a folder above the root of the website and modified the physical paths. This is not an ideal solution as the path will change on different machines, but I''m going to live with it for now.\r\n<h2>Install the Public Templates</h2>\r\nI used the EPiServer deployment centre to do this. It needs your website to be set up in IIS before it can access it. Create a new IIS website pointing to your EPiServer site. Set the physical path to your site directory and set a host name (that you can put in your hosts file to access the site).\r\n\r\nStart the EPiServer DeploymentÂ CentreÂ and select "Install Public Templates". Select your website from the list and click install.\r\n\r\nThis should add a Templates directory to your website and add some pages to the database too.\r\n<h2 style="font-size: 1.5em;">Move assemblies</h2>\r\nAlso, move the referenced assemblies in the web project to a folder with your solution files so they can be checked in. Make sure you re-add the references to the projetc from the new location and set "Copy Local" to true.', 'Creating a new EPiServer 6 Solution', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '50-revision-17', '', '', '2010-05-10 16:15:07', '2010-05-10 15:15:07', '', 50, 'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/05/10/50-revision-17/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(103, 1, '2010-05-10 16:15:27', '2010-05-10 15:15:27', '<div id="_mcePaste">\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">To create a new EPiServer 6 project you have 2 options. Either use the Deployment Centre (installed with EPiServer) or use the EPiServer Visual Studio template.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">The biggest problem with using the deployment tool is that it creates an IIS 7 website on your machine and references files and assemblies (in the Program Files folder) on your machine. This is fine if you are the only person in the team and work on the same machine all the time, and are happy to install EPiServer on your web server. It also creates the website in IIS 7 which is not ideal if you are running IIS6 on the web server.</div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste"></div>\r\n<div id="_mcePaste">I''m going to go through the steps required to create a new EPiServer project that can be run from the Visual Studio development web server and checked into source control, and most importantly will work when a colleague checks out a version.</div>\r\n</div>\r\n</div>\r\n<h3><span style="font-weight: normal;">Just an EPiServer site</span></h3>\r\nOpen Visual Studio 2008 and create a new project using the EPiServer Project template. The visual studio template comes bundled with the main EPiServer 6 download.\r\n\r\nNext, create a new database. Open the EPiServer Deployment Center, and select Install SQL Server Database. Update the website connection string with the new database details.\r\n\r\nNext, go to the website properties page, and on the Web tab, remove the virtual path. And in the EPiServer.config file change the siteUrl in the siteSettings element.\r\n\r\nNow you should be able to launch the website and navigate to <strong>http://localhost:6666/EPiServer</strong> and login using your Windows credentials.\r\n<h3><span style="font-weight: normal;">Move the Program Files</span></h3>\r\nThe EPiServer.config file contains a virtualPath section, with provider entries that have paths to files on your local drive. This will be a problem when you try to check in the website to source control, or publish the webiste.\r\n\r\nTo fix this we need to copy the files to the website folder and specify a new provider type.\r\n\r\nCopy the whole EPiServer folder from C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer to your website directory. I want to keep the folder structure in tact, the less we have to tinker with it the better I think (although I have deleted the help folders - they''re huge!). <strong>Be sure to rename it otherwise the path provider won''t kick in.</strong>\r\n\r\nNext update the EPiServer.config provider entries, for example:\r\n\r\n&lt;add name="UIFiles" virtualPath="~/EPiServer/CMS/" physicalPath="C:\\Program Files (x86)\\EPiServer\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS" type="EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider,EPiServer" /&gt;\r\n\r\nbecomes\r\n\r\n&lt;add name="UIFiles" virtualPath="~/EPiServer/CMS/" physicalPath="~\\EPiServerFiles\\CMS\\6.0.530.0\\Application\\UI\\CMS" type="Cubeworks.EPiServer6Site.RelativePathProvider,Cubeworks.EPiServer6Site" /&gt;\r\n\r\nNotice I have changed the type of provider to RelativePathProvider. (You may need to make a small change to the web.config file to make the website pickup the new configuration.)\r\n\r\n<strong>RelativePathProvider</strong>\r\n<pre class="brush:csharp">public class RelativePathProvider : EPiServer.Web.Hosting.VirtualPathNonUnifiedProvider\r\n{\r\n	public RelativePathProvider(string providerName, NameValueCollection configParameters)\r\n		: base(providerName, FixConfig(configParameters))\r\n	{\r\n	}\r\n	private static NameValueCollection FixConfig(NameValueCollection configParameters)\r\n	{\r\n		var virtualPath = configParameters["physicalPath"] ?? String.Empty;\r\n		if(virtualPath.StartsWith("~"))\r\n			configParameters["physicalPath"] = HostingEnvironment.MapPath(virtualPath);\r\n		return configParameters;\r\n	}\r\n}</pre>\r\nFor the PageFiles, Globals, and Documents folders, I''ve simply moved them into a folder above the root of the website and modified the physical paths. This is not an ideal solution as the path will change on different machines, but I''m going to live with it for now.\r\n<h2>Install the Public Templates</h2>\r\nI used the EPiServer deployment centre to do this. It needs your website to be set up in IIS before it can access it. Create a new IIS website pointing to your EPiServer site. Set the physical path to your site directory and set a host name (that you can put in your hosts file to access the site).\r\n\r\nStart the EPiServer DeploymentÂ CentreÂ and select "Install Public Templates". Select your website from the list and click install.\r\n\r\nThis should add a Templates directory to your website and add some pages to the database too.\r\n<h2 style="font-size: 1.5em;">Move assemblies</h2>\r\nAlso, move the referenced assemblies in the web project to a folder with your solution files so they can be checked in. Make sure you re-add the references to the projetc from the new location and set "Copy Local" to true.', 'Creating a new EPiServer 6 Solution', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '50-revision-18', '', '', '2010-05-10 16:15:27', '2010-05-10 15:15:27', '', 50, 'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/05/10/50-revision-18/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
