(140, 1, '2010-04-21 11:47:27', '2010-04-21 10:47:27', '<span> </span>\r\n<pre>not-null property references a null or transient value ContactDetails.Account</pre>\r\nThis happened because of a circular reference. A new (transient) Account object had a new ContactDetails object. When I tried to save the Account object, eitther the Account or ContactDetails object had a reference to a transient object.\r\n\r\nSolution: Save the Account before adding the ContactDetails, so the ContactDetails gets a reference to a persisted Account.', 'NHibernate Errors', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '64-revision-4', '', '', '2010-04-21 11:47:27', '2010-04-21 10:47:27', '', 64, 'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/04/21/64-revision-4/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(141, 1, '2010-06-29 14:27:17', '2010-06-29 13:27:17', 'Using AJAX to send a request to an MVC action protected with a <strong>ValidateAntiForgeryToken</strong> attribute requires that you send the token along with the request data. I''ve simply copied the value from the hidden input element (generated using <strong>Html.AntiForgeryToken</strong> in the view). Here''s the basic JavaScript:\n<pre class="brush:javascript">function getAntiForgeryToken()\n{\n	var tokenElement = $(''input[name=__RequestVerificationToken]'');\n	var token = $(tokenElement).val();\n	return token;\n}</pre>\nAnd the code for making the AJAX request uses the token in its request data:\n<pre class="brush:javascript">$.post(''/test.html'', {__RequestVerificationToken : getAntiForgeryToken() },\n	function (data) {\n		$("p.message").html(data);\n	}, ''json'');</pre>\n<strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">References</span></strong>\n\n<a href="http://api.jquery.com/jQuery.post/">http://api.jquery.com/jQuery.post/</a>\n\n<a href="http://haacked.com/archive/2009/04/02/anatomy-of-csrf-attack.aspx">http://haacked.com/archive/2009/04/02/anatomy-of-csrf-attack.aspx</a>', 'ASP.NET MVC Anti Forgery Token and Ajax request', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '124-autosave', '', '', '2010-06-29 14:27:17', '2010-06-29 13:27:17', '', 124, 'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/06/29/124-autosave/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(142, 1, '2010-02-27 21:50:32', '2010-02-27 21:50:32', '<p>I''ve just spent a lunch break getting a Wordpress site up and running for my blog. I was pleasantly surprised at how easy it is to set up. The Wordpress <a title="Wordpress installation instructions" href="http://codex.wordpress.org/Installing_WordPress#Famous_5-Minute_Install">Famous 5-Minute Install</a> documentation set it out very clearly.</p>\r\n<p>Here''s what I did:</p>\r\n<p>Installed PHP on my development machine with IIS7 (probably the trickiest part)</p>\r\n<ul>\r\n<li><a title="PHP documentation" href="http://www.php.net/manual/en/install.windows.iis7.php">Enable FastCGI support in IIS7</a></li>\r\n<li>Created an IIS7 website, unzip Wordpress site there</li>\r\n<li>Installed MySQL and MySQL Administrator (part of the MySQL Tools download) from <a title="MySQL Downloads" href="http://dev.mysql.com/downloads/">the MySQL site</a></li>\r\n<li>Used MySQL Administrator to created a new MySQL database and a new user for that database</li>\r\n<li>Edit wp-config.php in the Wordpress site<a title="wp-config.php settings" href="http://codex.wordpress.org/Installing_WordPress#Step_3:_Set_up_wp-config.php"> to point to your database</a></li>\r\n<li>Browse to the installation page and it''s as easy as that</li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<p>Next, I created a MySQL database on my hosting provider and uploaded the website to the web server, changing the wp-config.php file to point to the new database.</p>\r\n<p>I did have to edit the database table wp_options to update the URL of the website because it was going to http://localhost when I tried to go to the admin pages.</p>\r\n', 'Wordpress in a lunch break', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '3-revision-5', '', '', '2010-02-27 21:50:32', '2010-02-27 21:50:32', '', 3, 'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/02/27/3-revision-5/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(143, 1, '2010-02-27 21:06:03', '2010-02-27 21:06:03', 'This technique came about because of a website with multiple country home pages, and one global home page that lets you choose a country. The idea is that the user should not have to choose a county every time they visit the site, instead a cookie should store their selection so they can be taken back to theirÂ preferredÂ country home page. When you visit a countrys home page a cookie is set:\r\n\r\n<pre class="brush:csharp">\r\nvar aCookie = new HttpCookie("last_visited_global_homepage_url")\r\n		{\r\n			Value = Request.Url.PathAndQuery,\r\n			Expires = DateTime.Now.AddMonths(1)\r\n		};\r\nResponse.Cookies.Add(aCookie);\r\n</pre>\r\n\r\nThen you are redirected back to that county on your next visit:\r\n<pre class="brush:csharp">\r\n	var cookie = Request.Cookies["last_visited_global_homepage_url"];\r\n	var isNotInternalRequest =  Page.Request.UrlReferrer == null ? true : Page.Request.UrlReferrer.Host != Request.Url.Host;\r\n\r\n	if (isNotInternalRequest &amp;&amp; cookie != null)\r\n	{\r\n		//redirect to last country page\r\n		Response.Redirect(cookie.Value);\r\n	}\r\n</pre>\r\nThe important part in the code above is the isNotInternalRequest check, whichÂ makes sure that you can go back to the landing page and select a new country.', 'Using cookies to redirect a user to the last page they visted', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '18-revision-8', '', '', '2010-02-27 21:06:03', '2010-02-27 21:06:03', '', 18, 'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/02/27/18-revision-8/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(144, 1, '2010-05-15 23:15:32', '2010-05-15 22:15:32', '<strong>Get the start page PageReference:</strong>\r\n<pre class="brush:csharp">PageReference.StartPage</pre>\r\nA PageRefernce is basically a wrapper for integer ids. It also containsÂ convenienceÂ methods as in the above example which simply gets the start page id from the configuration:\r\n<pre class="brush:csharp">EPiServer.Configuration.Settings.Instance.PageStartId</pre>\r\nThe PageData class holds information about the page such as name and URL. It makes pageÂ propertiesÂ available through the property "Property" (PropertyDataCollection).\r\n\r\n<strong>Get PageData from a PageReference:</strong>\r\n<pre class="brush:csharp">DataFactory.Instance.GetPage(PageReference.StartPage)</pre>', 'EPiServer Snippets', 'A work in progress cheat sheet of EPiServer code snippets.', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '89-revision-7', '', '', '2010-05-15 23:15:32', '2010-05-15 22:15:32', '', 89, 'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/05/15/89-revision-7/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
