gin with the new user (when I did this I got a page which said "Root folder" with no menus at the top of left, I had to click "My Settings" to get a screen with aÂ menu)</li>\r\n</ul>\r\nAnd now I can see I have a shiny new CMS to play with.\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-159" title="a-new-episerver6-site" src="http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/a-new-episerver6-site-600x357.jpg" alt="The empty page tree of a new EPiServer 6 site" width="600" height="357" />\r\n\r\nThis is a good time to set some permissions for the group I created earlier. I''ve done this in Admin Mode o the "Set access rights" page. This will give me permissions to create pages under the website root.\r\n\r\n<img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-164" title="episerver6-set-access-rights" src="http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/episerver6-set-access-rights-600x303.jpg" alt="The EPiServer 6 admin rights admin screen" width="600" height="303" />\r\n\r\nNow I need a page template so I can start adding some content to the CMS! I''ve added a new template file using the EPiServer Visual Studio template. This added an aspx file to the project (which inherits from EPiServer. TemplatePage). A popup box asked me if I''d like to register the page type, I clicked "no", and did this myself in EPiServer admin mode after renaming the file. I also added a long string property for some text.\r\n\r\nUseful resources:\r\n\r\n<a href="http://sdk.episerver.com/library/cms5/Getting%20Started/Setting%20Up%20a%20New%20EPiServer%20Site%20with%20Visual%20Studio.htm">http://sdk.episerver.com/library/cms5/Getting%20Started/Setting%20Up%20a%20New%20EPiServer%20Site%20with%20Visual%20Studio.htm</a>', 'Creating an EPiServer 6 Site', 'If you want to run EPiServer 6 in Visual Studio as a starting point for a project or just to try out some code, you can use the Visual Studio integration tools to get a new site up and running fast. I''ve noted down the steps her