(177, 1, '2010-07-11 08:44:21', '2010-07-11 07:44:21', 'The EPiServer MenuList control may be useful for creating the primary navigation for a site, but if you need more than a simple list of top-level pages, you can use the PageTree control.\n\nI''m going to create a css drop-down menu showing 2 levels of pages. This is the code for the PageTree control:\n<pre class="brush:xhtml">\n<div id="_mcePaste">&lt;EPiServer:PageTree ShowRootPage="false" PageLink="&lt;%#PageReference.StartPage %&gt;" NumberOfLevels="2" ExpandAll="true" runat="server" ID="PrimaryNavigation"&gt;\n	&lt;IndentTemplate&gt;\n		&lt;ul&gt;\n	&lt;/IndentTemplate&gt;\n	&lt;ItemHeaderTemplate&gt;\n		&lt;li&gt;\n	&lt;/ItemHeaderTemplate&gt;\n	&lt;ItemTemplate&gt;\n		&lt;EPiServer:Property ID="Property1" PropertyName="PageLink" runat="server" /&gt;\n	&lt;/ItemTemplate&gt;\n	&lt;ItemFooterTemplate&gt;\n		&lt;/li&gt;\n	&lt;/ItemFooterTemplate&gt;\n	&lt;UnindentTemplate&gt;\n		&lt;/ul&gt;\n	&lt;/UnindentTemplate&gt;\n&lt;/EPiServer:PageTree&gt;</div></pre>\nNote the properties in the parent element - ShowRootPage (whether to show the start page), PageLink (the starting page for the menu), ExpandAll (renders a menu item for every page), NumberOfLevels (\n\nI''ve put this on the start page template of my EPiServer site as it''s just an exercise. Ideally it would be contained in an ascx user control that would be referenced from the master page of the site. So this renders all the markup I need for my menu, it''s simply HTML lists.\n\n<img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-174" title="primary-navigation-lists" src="http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/primary-navigation-lists-600x366.jpg" alt="The primary navigation is rendered as a HTML lists" width="600" height="366" />\n\nFirebug shows the HTML lists rendered by the PageTree control and my templates.\n<img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-175" title="primary-nav-markup-in-firebug" src="http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/primary-nav-markup-in-firebug-600x430.jpg" alt="Firebug shows the markup of the navigation lists" width="600" height="430" />\n\nNext it''s just a matter of applying some css style to get the menu looking and behaving a bit more like a menu. I''ve wrapped the PageTree control with a div element with an id of "priary-nav" so I can target it with css rules.\n<pre class="brush:css">div#primary-nav ul\n{\n	list-style-image: none;\n	list-style-position: outside;\n	list-style-type: none;\n	margin: 0;\n	padding: 0;\n	text-align:center;\n}\n	div#primary-nav li\n	{\n		float: left;\n		background-color: #ccc;\n		width:100px;\n		text-align:center;\n	}\n		div#primary-nav li a\n		{\n			padding:5px;\n			display:block;\n		}\n\ndiv#primary-nav li ul\n{\n	width:100px;\n	position: absolute;\n	left: -999em;\n}\n	div#primary-nav li ul li\n	{\n		background-color: #eee;\n	}\n\ndiv#primary-nav li:hover ul\n{\n	left: auto;\n}</pre>\nAnd with style applied the menu looks like this:\n\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-176" title="primary-navigation-with-css" src="http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/primary-navigation-with-css.jpg" alt="The navigation menu with css rules applied" width="369" height="207" />\n\nBuilding on this example should enable me to quickly build drop-down menus for a number of scenarios - there are a lot more properties and templates of the PageTree control to explore, and understanding the basics is the first step to building more complex navigation to fit the requirements of a specific site.\n\nUseful links:\n\nhttp://www.frederikvig.com/tag/episerver-web-controls/', 'EPiServer PageTree for primary navigation', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '170-revision-4', '', '', '2010-07-11 08:44:21', '2010-07-11 07:44:21', '', 170, 'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/07/11/170-revision-4/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(178, 1, '2010-03-31 14:25:46', '2010-03-31 13:25:46', 'I had to fix a bug today where the client reported that the dates on a page were all in French. She had set her browser language to French (apparently without realising).\r\n\r\nLocalisation is an area that I am ashamedly unfamiliar with, so I did some digging.\r\n\r\nI set my browser language to French (fr) and sure enough the dates appeared in French. I looked at Thread.CurrentThread.CurrentCulture.EnglishName and that was "French", so the culture was being picked up from the browser.\r\n\r\nAs this site is not set up for localisation, I opted to override the current culture in the web.config:\r\n\r\n<pre class="brush:csharp">\r\n&lt;configuration&gt;\r\n    &lt;system.web&gt;\r\n        &lt;globalization culture="en-GB" uiCulture="en-GB" /&gt;\r\n    &lt;/system.web&gt;\r\n&lt;/configuration&gt;</pre>\r\n\r\n<blockquote>The culture attribute enables you to define the culture to use for processing incoming requests, whereas the uiCulture attribute enables you define the default culture needed to process any resource files in the application. (Pro. ASP.Net 3.5)</blockquote>\r\n\r\nThat fixed my bug and the code stayed the same but gave me an English date for the GB culture.\r\n\r\n<pre class="brush:csharp">\r\nCurrentItem.Published.ToLongDateString()\r\n</pre>', 'DateTime, ToString(), and CurrentCulture', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '35-revision-10', '', '', '2010-03-31 14:25:46', '2010-03-31 13:25:46', '', 35, 'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/03/31/35-revision-10/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
