(189, 1, '2010-08-12 15:34:10', '2010-08-12 14:34:10', '<h3><span style="font-weight: normal;">Typical workflow</span></h3>\n<h3></h3>\n<h3>git commit -a<span style="font-weight: normal;"> - commit staged and unstaged changes to loacl repository</span></h3>\n<span style="font-weight: normal;">git pull origin [branch]</span>\n\n<span style="font-weight: normal;">git push origin [branch]</span>\n<h3></h3>\n<h3></h3>\n<h3>Core Commands</h3>\n<strong>git status</strong>\n\nUse to see the status of the files an the current branch. Use <strong>git diff</strong> to get more details.\n\n<strong>git add</strong>\n\nStages files to beÂ committed. Remember that if you stage a file, then edit it, you need to stage it again for the latest edit to be committed. Use <strong>-A</strong> to stage all.\n\n<strong>git diff</strong>\n\nIf you have changed a staged file, use diff to see the details. UseÂ <strong>â€“-staged<span style="font-weight: normal;"> or </span>--cached<span style="font-weight: normal;"> to see the staged differences.</span></strong>\n\n<strong>git commit</strong>\n\nCommit staged changes to local repository. Use the <strong>-a</strong> options to commit unstaged changes (to tracked files)\n\n<strong>git rm</strong>\n\nRemoved a file from the staging area, and also from the working directory if it exists there. Use <strong>git rm --cached </strong>to remove a file from the staging area.\n\n<strong>gitk</strong>\n\nVisual log history.\n<h3>Undoing Things</h3>\n<strong>git checkout [file]</strong>\n\n<strong><span style="font-weight: normal;">Checks out a file overwriting any local changes. Use </span></strong><strong>git checkout . </strong>to lose all local changes.\n\n<strong> </strong><strong>git reset HEAD [files]</strong>\n\nRemoves files from the staging area.\n\n<strong>git reset [hash]</strong>\n\nReset the current head to the specified state.\n\n<strong>git reset --hard</strong>\n\nMatches the working tree and index to that of the tree being switched to, losing staged changes.\n<h3>Working with Branches</h3>\n<strong>git branch</strong>\n\nLists your local branches, use <strong>git branch -r</strong> to list the remote branches.\n\n<strong>git checkout </strong><strong><em>branch</em></strong>\n\nCheckout a branch to the working directory.\n<h3>Merging</h3>\n<strong>git merge [hash]</strong>\n\nMerge a commit from another branch.\n<div><strong>git checkout master</strong></div>\n<div><strong>git merge beta</strong></div>\n<div><strong>git push origin master</strong></div>\n<div>Merge beta branch into master branch</div>\n<h3>Working with Remotes</h3>\n<strong>git remote show [remote-name]</strong>\n\nGet the details of the remote repository, including branches.\n\n<strong>git remote</strong>\n\nLists your remote repositories.\n\n<strong>git fetch [remote-name]</strong>\n\nFetch changes from remote repository, but don''t update the working directory (use <strong>rebase </strong>for that).\n\n<strong>git pull [remote-name]</strong>\n\nFetch changes from remote repository and update the working directory.\n\n<strong>git push [remote-name] [branch-name]</strong>\n\nPush your local commits to a remote repository.\n\n<strong>Tricks</strong>\n\n<strong>git update-index</strong> --assume-unchanged connectionString.config\n\nIgnore a tracked file\n\n<strong><span style="text-decoration: underline;">Useful References</span></strong>\n\n<a href="http://cheat.errtheblog.com/s/git">http://cheat.errtheblog.com/s/git</a>', 'Git Shortcuts', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '115-revision-11', '', '', '2010-08-12 15:34:10', '2010-08-12 14:34:10', '', 115, 'http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/index.php/2010/08/12/115-revision-11/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(190, 1, '2010-08-22 08:48:56', '2010-08-22 07:48:56', 'The EPiServer MenuList control may be useful for creating the primary navigation for a site, but if you need more than a simple list of top-level pages, you can use the PageTree control.\n<pre class="brush: js">function foo()\n{\n}</pre>\nI''m going to create a css drop-down menu showing 2 levels of pages. This is the code for the PageTree control:\n<pre class="brush: xhtml">&lt;EPiServer:PageTree ShowRootPage="false" PageLink="&lt;%#PageReference.StartPage %&gt;" NumberOfLevels="2" ExpandAll="true" runat="server" ID="PrimaryNavigation"&gt;\n	&lt;IndentTemplate&gt;\n		&lt;ul&gt;\n	&lt;/IndentTemplate&gt;\n	&lt;ItemHeaderTemplate&gt;\n		&lt;li&gt;\n	&lt;/ItemHeaderTemplate&gt;\n	&lt;ItemTemplate&gt;\n		&lt;EPiServer:Property ID="Property1" PropertyName="PageLink" runat="server" /&gt;\n	&lt;/ItemTemplate&gt;\n	&lt;ItemFooterTemplate&gt;\n		&lt;/li&gt;\n	&lt;/ItemFooterTemplate&gt;\n	&lt;UnindentTemplate&gt;\n		&lt;/ul&gt;\n	&lt;/UnindentTemplate&gt;\n&lt;/EPiServer:PageTree&gt;</pre>\nNote the properties in the parent element - ShowRootPage (whether to show the start page), PageLink (the starting page for the menu), ExpandAll (renders a menu item for every page), NumberOfLevels (the number of levels to render out).\n\nI''ve put this on the start page template of my EPiServer site as it''s just an exercise. Ideally it would be contained in an ascx user control that would be referenced from the master page of the site. So this renders all the markup I need for my menu, it''s simply HTML lists.\n\n<img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-174" title="primary-navigation-lists" src="http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/primary-navigation-lists-600x366.jpg" alt="The primary navigation is rendered as a HTML lists" width="600" height="366" />\n\nFirebug shows the HTML lists rendered by the PageTree control and my templates.\n<img class="alignnone size-medium wp-image-175" title="primary-nav-markup-in-firebug" src="http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/primary-nav-markup-in-firebug-600x430.jpg" alt="Firebug shows the markup of the navigation lists" width="600" height="430" />\n\nNext it''s just a matter of applying some css style to get the menu looking and behaving a bit more like a menu. I''ve wrapped the PageTree control with a div element with an id of "priary-nav" so I can target it with css rules.\n<pre class="brush:css">div#primary-nav ul\n{\n	list-style-image: none;\n	list-style-position: outside;\n	list-style-type: none;\n	margin: 0;\n	padding: 0;\n	text-align:center;\n}\n	div#primary-nav li\n	{\n		float: left;\n		background-color: #ccc;\n		width:100px;\n		text-align:center;\n	}\n		div#primary-nav li a\n		{\n			padding:5px;\n			display:block;\n		}\n\ndiv#primary-nav li ul\n{\n	width:100px;\n	position: absolute;\n	left: -999em;\n}\n	div#primary-nav li ul li\n	{\n		background-color: #eee;\n	}\n\ndiv#primary-nav li:hover ul\n{\n	left: auto;\n}</pre>\nAnd with style applied the menu looks like this:\n\n<img class="alignnone size-full wp-image-176" title="primary-navigation-with-css" src="http://www.jonathansewell.co.uk/wp-content/uploads/2010/07/primary-navigation-with-css.jpg" alt="The navigation menu with css rules applied" width="369" height="207" />\n\nBuilding on this example should enable me to quickly build drop-down menus for a number of scenarios - there are a lot more properties and templates of the PageTree control to explore, and understanding the basics is the first step to building more complex navigation to fit the requirements of a specific site.\n\nUseful links:\n\nhttp://www.frederikvig.com/tag/episerver-web-controls/', 'EPiServer PageTree for primary navigation', '', 'inherit', 'open', 'open', '', '170-autosave', '', '', '2010-08-22 08:48:56', '2010-08-22 07:48:56', '', 170, 'http://localhost/jsewell_mywordpressblog/index.php/2010/08/22/170-autosave/', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
